{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11378"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11378"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.05,0.33,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44564"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4023"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29449"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44564"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78 year-old male presents to his GP with a pigmented lesion on his right forearm. He undergoes an excisional biopsy with 2mm margins, which demonstrates a melanoma of Breslow thickness 4.5mm. He has a palpable lymph node in the ipsilateral axilla, and FNA demonstrates malignant cells. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA wide local excision with 2cm margins is planned for his forearm lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate management of this patient\u0027s axillary findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Targeted immunotherapy","Interferon-alpha adjuvant therapy","Radiation therapy to the axilla","Sentinel lymph node biopsy","Axillary clearance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a malignant melanoma with evidence of metastatic disease to the axilla. Based on the breslow thickness (BT) this patient requires WLE with 2cm margins. Regarding management of the axilla, given the presence of clinical nodal disease, this patient requires an\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary clearance\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0to remove the cancer within the draining lymph node basin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon-alpha adjuvant therapy\u003C/strong\u003E has been used as adjuvant therapy in high-risk melanoma cases. However, its benefits in terms of overall survival are modest, and it is associated with significant side effects. It is typically considered in cases of high-risk melanoma after surgical management, but in this scenario where there is confirmed lymph node involvement, it might not be the most appropriate initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation therapy to the axilla\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used as the primary treatment for melanoma in the lymph nodes. It may be considered as adjuvant therapy after lymph node dissection or in cases where surgery is not feasible. However, in this scenario where there is confirmed lymph node involvement, surgical management is usually the primary approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETargeted immunotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E, such as checkpoint inhibitors like pembrolizumab or ipilimumab, has revolutionised the treatment of advanced melanoma. However, in this case where there is confirmed lymph node involvement, surgical management to remove the affected lymph nodes is typically the initial approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe purpose of a\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Esentinel lymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is to identify occult metastatic cells (if not identified based on clinical exam and/or US). The indications for performing this are no clinical nodal disease and BT \u0026gt;1mm or \u0026gt;0.75mm plus high-risk features such as lymphovascular invasion, Clark IV/V and ulceration. This patient already has confirmed malignancy therefore this will not provide further information.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Axillary clearance is recommended for patients with clinical nodal disease","Sentinel lymph node biopsy aims to detect clinically occult metastatic disease in patients with high risk features"],"references":["Cancer Council Australia Melanoma Guidelines Working Party. Clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of melanoma. Sydney: Melanoma Institute Australia. Cited Oct 8 2021"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29449"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11378"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29449"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-23T12:46:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-23T12:46:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4023"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44564"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https